AWS EFS (Elastic File System)


What is EFS?

EFS (Elastic File System) is a fully managed shared file storage service provided by AWS.

It allows multiple EC2 instances to access the same files at the same time.



Simple Definition

EFS is a shared storage that can be mounted by multiple EC2 instances simultaneously.



Real-Life Example

Imagine a Google Drive folder.

Multiple people can access the same folder.
If one person uploads a file, everyone can see it.

👉 EFS works the same way for EC2 instances.




Why Do We Use EFS?:
Share files between multiple EC2 instances.
Automatically increases storage when data grows.
No need to manage storage manually.
Highly available across multiple Availability Zones.



Features:
Shared file storage
Supports multiple EC2 instances
Auto Scales (No fixed size)
Highly Available
Fully Managed by AWS


Uses NFS (Network File System) protocol
EFS vs EBS
EFS	EBS
Shared Storage	Single EC2 Storage
Multiple EC2 Instances	One EC2 Instance
Auto Scales	Fixed Size
File Storage	Block Storage


Use Cases
Web Applications
Shared Application Files
WordPress
Content Management Systems
Machine Learning
Shared Logs



